The paper discusses the analysis of Deep Neural Networks (DNNs) using the information bottleneck (IB) principle, which is a concept from information theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is a likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the optimal architecture, number of layers, and features/connections at each layer, which are related to the bifurcation points of the information bottleneck tradeoff. This suggests that the paper could also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses the hierarchical representations at the layered network, which could be related to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category.
